LAGOS  Island Local Government, in collaboration with the state, will soon relocate traders affected by Apongbon fire incident. Council Chairman Prince Adetoyese Olusi gave an update on the council’s efforts, in partnership with federal and state governments, to return normalcy and ensure that residents have their means of livelihood back. He said: “We are working to see that our people affected by the unfortunate incident have their lives back. “Relocating them is a priority for us, just as ensuring that safety is never compromised in the area again.   Insecurity: Fintiri reviews curfew for Ramadan lectures     Thought Pyramid hosts art exhibition     ‘Restriction of homeowners unlawful’   “As a council, we are in lockstep with federal and state governments in doing the needful, to fix the problem and ensure there is no repeat. “As a mark of our commitment to get affected traders back on their feet, in weeks from now, in collaboration with the state government, they would be moved to new and conducive trading points in the downtown commercial hub of Lagos Island to continue with their trading. “In collaboration with the central government, we are working to ensure that the area affected by the incident is cleaned up and every trading activity and illegality, permanently disengaged at the Apongbon/Berger under bridge.” Olusi enjoined the people to be law-abiding to help government fulfil its mandate.